{
  "task_id": "data_computation_task6",
  "task_name": "Definite Integral Computation and Visualization",
  "description": "Compute 4 definite integrals using symbolic and 3 numerical methods, generate publication-quality visualizations.",
  "skills": [
    "sympy",
    "scientific-visualization"
  ],
  "prompt": "I am a numerical analysis student, and I need to complete a coursework project comparing numerical integration methods. Please compute the symbolic and numerical solutions for the following 4 definite integrals, and generate visualizations:\n\n1. $\\int_0^{\\pi} \\sin(x)\\,dx$\n2. $\\int_0^{1} e^{-x^2}\\,dx$\n3. $\\int_1^{e} \\ln(x)\\,dx$\n4. $\\int_0^{\\pi/2} \\sqrt{\\sin(x)}\\,dx$\n\nFor each integral, apply 3 numerical methods (Trapezoidal rule N=100, Simpson's rule N=100, Gaussian quadrature) and compute the numerical approximation and error.\n\nOutput integrals.json as a JSON object with an \"integrals\" key containing an array of 4 objects, i.e. {\"integrals\": [...]}, each object containing integral_id, integrand, bounds, exact_numeric, trapezoidal, simpson, gaussian_quadrature, and the error for each method.\n\nGenerate 5 figures: integral_1.png through integral_4.png (function curve with shaded area and exact value annotation) and error_comparison.png (a grouped bar chart comparing errors of the 3 methods across all 4 integrals on a logarithmic scale). All figures should be publication quality with LaTeX labels.",
  "outputs": [
    "integrals.json",
    "integral_1.png",
    "integral_2.png",
    "integral_3.png",
    "integral_4.png",
    "error_comparison.png"
  ],
  "category": "data_computation",
  "aggregation": {
    "strategy": "weighted_sum"
  },
  "evaluators": [
    {
      "id": "json_exists",
      "type": "objective_usability",
      "op_func": "file_exists",
      "description": "Check that integrals.json exists",
      "weight": 3,
      "op_args": {
        "path": "integrals.json",
        "min_size": 1
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "json_valid",
      "type": "objective_usability",
      "op_func": "json_valid",
      "description": "Check that integrals.json is valid JSON",
      "weight": 3,
      "op_args": {
        "path": "integrals.json"
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "json_exists"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "integral1_correct",
      "type": "objective_usability",
      "op_func": "json_array_item_check",
      "description": "Check integral 1 exact_numeric ≈ 2.0",
      "weight": 8,
      "op_args": {
        "path": "integrals.json",
        "array_path": "integrals",
        "match": {
          "integral_id": 1
        },
        "checks": [
          {
            "field": "exact_numeric",
            "type": "near",
            "expected": 2.0,
            "tolerance": 0.001
          }
        ]
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "json_valid"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "integral2_correct",
      "type": "objective_usability",
      "op_func": "json_array_item_check",
      "description": "Check integral 2 exact_numeric ≈ 0.7468",
      "weight": 8,
      "op_args": {
        "path": "integrals.json",
        "array_path": "integrals",
        "match": {
          "integral_id": 2
        },
        "checks": [
          {
            "field": "exact_numeric",
            "type": "near",
            "expected": 0.7468,
            "tolerance": 0.001
          }
        ]
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "json_valid"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "integral3_correct",
      "type": "objective_usability",
      "op_func": "json_array_item_check",
      "description": "Check integral 3 exact_numeric ≈ 1.0",
      "weight": 8,
      "op_args": {
        "path": "integrals.json",
        "array_path": "integrals",
        "match": {
          "integral_id": 3
        },
        "checks": [
          {
            "field": "exact_numeric",
            "type": "near",
            "expected": 1.0,
            "tolerance": 0.001
          }
        ]
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "json_valid"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "fig1_exists",
      "type": "objective_usability",
